  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are statutes that address money laundering in many jurisdictions around the world. These statutes are designed to criminalize the process of making illegally-gained proceeds appear legal, and they often include provisions for investigating, prosecuting, and punishing those involved in such activities.\n\nIn the United States, the primary federal statute addressing money laundering is the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, which is codified at **18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957**. These sections provide the legal framework for prosecuting individuals or entities that knowingly engage in financial transactions involving the proceeds of certain unlawful activities. Key provisions include:\n\n1. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** - Prohibits money laundering by criminalizing the financial transactions intended to promote illegal activities, conceal the nature or source of illegal proceeds, or avoid reporting requirements.\n2. **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** - Makes it illegal to engage in monetary transactions involving property derived from specified unlawful activity if the value of the property exceeds $10,000.\n\nIn addition to federal laws, many states have their own statutes addressing money laundering.\n\nGlobally, many countries have enacted laws to combat money laundering, often following international standards set by organizations such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, which is an intergovernmental body that sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) efforts. \n\nSome notable international examples include:\n\n1. **European Union**: The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) that member states must implement into their national laws.\n2. **United Kingdom**: The **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)** is the principal legislation addressing money laundering in the UK.\n3. **Canada**: The **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act** is the primary law addressing money laundering in Canada.\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement measures to detect and prevent money laundering, such as customer due diligence (CDD), record-keeping, and reporting of suspicious activities.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
